Here's my chance to live up to the NAMEDROPPERS moderator's
request to effect participation from everyone who subscribes.
I only regret that I am not a "domain guru." (or maybe I don't! &lt;grin&gt;)
----------------------------------------------------------------

Rudy writes:

&gt;What is the "name policy" behind CSNET going to domain names like .CS.NET?
&gt;Wasn't the plan to have names like UMASS.EDU registered at NIC which
&gt;pointed to some domain server at CSNET which had MF records for the
&gt;phonenet site "umass"?

Yes, I believe the latter to be correct.
In fact, a conversation that I had with Charlotte Mooers at CSNET
yesterday appeared to confirm that.


&gt;Does this first attempt at using domains for another transport/administration
&gt;network means that we will have domain names like:
&gt;    network            domain names
&gt;    -------            ---------------------
&gt;    BITNET            BIT.NET
&gt;    MAILNET            MAIL.NET or EDUCOM.NET
&gt;    UUCP            UCB-UUCP.NET, SEISMO-UUCP.NET, etc.
&gt;or is this some transition mechanism to get thru the short term?

No, I think not.  I think the above scenario (?) might provide
more mess than it is worth and perhaps the question of internetworking
syntax is best left alone until such time that the local DDNnet
addressing syntax is fully agreed upon.  Only then, would there exist
a rational choice to consider changing the internetworking syntax.


--- Gligor Tashkovich

INTERNET: RMXJ%CORNELLA.BITNET@WISCVM.WISC.EDU

P.S. Using my Internet address as an example, how might someone
     implement Rudy's concern? RMXJ%CORNELLA.BIT.NET@WISCVM.WISC.EDU????

